      "content": "thanks for those. they're a good start but a bit surface-level for a high school policy round. my students need to move past the basics. can you expand on the economic side of it? specifically, how do proponents argue that stricter enforcement protects domestic labor markets and prevents the straining of public infrastructure/social services? i want them to have the most sophisticated version of the \"economic protectionism\" argument possible.",
